2	// eval/e2e/lib/redteam-handlers.js - BESPOKE per-fixture wiring for eval/red-team/fixtures.json entries
3	// whose `input` is not a plain runnable EvidenceBundle (RT-D, RT-G, RT-H), or whose correct handling
4	// needs semantics the generic must_not-token evaluator (redteam.js) cannot express (RT-F's known,
5	// already-tracked xfail).
6	//
7	// This is INTENTIONALLY keyed by fixture id, not a generic mechanism: eval/red-team/fixtures.json's
8	// entries genuinely differ in shape (bundle vs fetch+honest/naive-bundle vs cookies+browser_script vs
9	// bare corpus strings), and several document their own precise "wired_now_by" instructions that this
10	// file follows directly, using modules that are ALREADY LIVE (evidence/crawler/extract.js,
11	// evidence/browser/oracle.js, breach/verifiers/index.js, facts/*). An id with no bespoke handler here
12	// falls through to redteam.js's generic bundle + must_not-token evaluator; an id that also has no
13	// generic path there is honestly skipped.
14	//
15	// Every handler returns {status, reason?} where status is one of:
16	//   caught    the live gate held.
17	//   escaped   the live gate did not hold - a fresh, real finding.
18	//   skipped   this handler cannot evaluate the entry as given (missing input fields).
19	//   xfail     the escape reproduced AND the fixture itself already declares it a known, tracked,
20	//             owned-elsewhere issue (current_status: 'verified_escapes_live_gate') - caution.md C-162
21	//             ("dismissals are per-item with a written reason") / Fleet Rule 4 (the red team records,
22	//             it does not fix). xfail counts neither as a fresh escape nor as a clean pass; it does not
23	//             fail this harness's exit code, but a genuinely NEW escape shape not matching the
24	//             documented one still reports 'escaped', never silently absorbed into the xfail.
25	//
26	// KNOWN, DOCUMENTED SCOPE LIMIT: RT-G's handler below only exercises the LIVE, direct half of that
27	// fixture's own "wired_now_by" (evidence/browser/oracle.js's classifyCookie() on the supplied
28	// cookies_pre_consent array). The second half - a full evidence/browser/observe() lane run against a
29	// scripted fake browser built from input.browser_script - is NOT implemented here. Building a
30	// contract-conforming fake browser (newPage/goto/settle/cookies/findConsentControl/clickConsent, per
31	// evidence/browser/observe.js's documented contract) is a real, separate piece of work; this is a
32	// deliberate, stated limit, not a silent gap.
